            "answer_text": "You have it backwards. Chemists first figured out weight of oxygen is 8 times the weight of hydrogen in water by electrolyzing water. Then it was figured out there are two hydrogens per water so hydrogen was assigned the molecular weight of 1. Oxygen was 16 times that so it became 16. A mole got defined as the number of particles in 1g of elemental hydrogen. It is a man-made number, no significance in nature. (2g hydrogen in gaseous form due to H2, rather than H) Oxygen hangs out as O2 so, it is assigned 16*2=32. All of it comes from H2O (water) ratios and 1 gram. ",
